\part{Main Material}

These notes very briefly summarize\footnotemark Chapters $2, 3, 5, 6$ from \textcite{mining-complex-networks}, focusing on data analysis of simple graphs.
As much of the material is review, these notes mostly provide an overview and the reader should see the original text for the specific details.
\footnotetext{Scattered throughout the notes are additional material that I found helpful.}

\section{Random Graphs}

The authors motivate the study of random graphs for the following applications:
\begin{itemize}
    \item As a set of conceptual and mathematical examples, with well understood properties.
    \item As models for empirical (real, complex) networks.
    \item As procedures to create synthetic networks, often for testing and benchmarking algorithms.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{ER graphs}

The Erd\"os-Renyi graph $\ER(n, p)$ has vertex set $V = \arange{n}$, with edges sampled iid from the support $\binom{V}{2}$ according to $\BernoulliD(p)$.
It is closely related to the Erd\"os process:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item $\ER_0$ has no edges
    \item $\ER_{t+1}$ adds a single edge to $\ER_t$, uniformly among all non-present edges
\end{enumerate}
where $\ER(n, p) = \ER_t$, where $t \sim \BinomialD(\binom{n}{2}, p)$, and hence it is often also called the Binomial graph.
The asymptotic behavior of ER graphs are incredibly well-understood, and we illustrate it with two examples, developed precisely in Section \ref{sec:er}.

\paragraph{Components and Connectivity:}
Let $\mean{k} = (n-1)p$ denote the expected average degree of $\ER(n, p)$.
For $\mean{k} < 1$, then asymptotically almost surely (aas), $\ER(n, p)$ ``looks like'' collections of small trees and uni-cycle components.
For $\mean{k} > 1$, then aas $\ER(n, p)$ ``looks like'' a single giant component of size $\Omega(n)$.
Indeed, the intuition for this phase transition is clear: it is the stability threshold of exponential growth!

If we write $p(n) = \frac{\ln n + c}{n}$, then the expected number of isolated nodes is aas $e^{-c}$.
This is the main barrier to connectivity, as if $p = \omega(\frac{\ln n}{n})$, then aas $\ER(n, p)$ is connected.

\paragraph{Motifs:}
Let $d(G) = \frac{1}{2} \mean{k} = \frac{\abs{E(G)}}{\abs{V(G)}}$ be the density of a graph, and consider $m(G) = \max_{H \subset G} d(H)$ the maximum subgraph density.
Then, $G$ will appear as a subgraph aas if and only if the densest subgraph will too, and moreover is $0$ or $1$ based on the thresholded probability $ p^* = n^{-1/m(G)} $.
Indeed, the intuition is clear for why the densest subgraph $H^*$ is the hardest to reproduce.
With $O(n^{V(H^*)})$ possible vertex sets where $H^*$ can appear, with $O(p^{E(H^*)})$ probability of this graph appearing, then $p^* = n^{-V(H^*) / E(H^*)}$ is indeed the transition point.

\subsection{Power-Law}

Significant empirical evidence supports that many properties of real-world networks exhibit power-law degree distributions, i.e. according to Zipf distribution with support over $\mathbb{Z}^+$,
\begin{equation}
    \label{eq:zipf}
    D \sim f(d) \propto d^{- \gamma}
    \qquad
    \Ev(D^k) \approx \frac{\gamma - 1}{\gamma - 1 - k}, \gamma > (k+1)
\end{equation}

The ER graph is a poor model for this.
Indeed, the degree of a vertex follows $\BinomialD(n-1, p)$, and thus as $n \to \infty$, then this degree follows $\PoissonD(\mean{k})$.
In particular, Poisson has an exponential tail, in contrast to a power-law tail.

The Barab\'asi–Albert (BA) preferential attachment process produces power-law graphs with $\gamma = 3$ (Section \ref{sec:ba}):
\begin{enumerate}
    \item $\mathcal{B}_1$ has a single vertex
    \item $\mathcal{B}_{t+1}$ adds a single vertex to $\mathcal{B}_t$, adding $m$ edges sampled with probability proportional to $\deg_{\mathcal{B}_t}(v)$.
\end{enumerate}
Indeed, if we use a \emph{continuum} approximation to the degree distribution, so that for vertex $v_i$,
$$
    \pdv{\deg(v_i)}{t} = m \frac{\deg(v_i)}{2mt} \implies \frac{\odif \deg(v_i)}{\deg(v_i)} = \frac{\odif{t}}{2t}
$$
and solving it, with the initial condition that $t_0 / t \sim U(0, 1)$, and $\deg(v_i) \big|_{t_0} = m$, then
$$
    \deg(v_i) = m \sqrt{\frac{t}{t_0}},
    \qquad
    \pdv{}{k} \Pr{\deg(v_i) \le k} = \pdv{}{k} \Pr{ \frac{t_0}{t} \ge \frac{m^2}{k^2} } = \pdv{}{k} \ab( 1 - \frac{m^2}{k^2} ) = 2m^2 k^{-3}
$$

\subsection{Chung-Lu and Configuration}

Another approach for better realism in our network models is to specifically enforce the degree distribution.
For a given degree sequence $\vb{d}$\footnotemark, we consider the uniform distribution over all graphs with $\vb{d}$ as its sequence.
\footnotetext{Not all degree sequences are realizable.
    The Havel-Hakimi theorem is illustrative, asserting handshaking and pigeonhole are sufficient and necessary.
    In practice, the Erd\"os-Gallai formula is efficient.}

A more theoretically pleasing model is to enforce degrees only in expectation, i.e. attaching edges independently:
\begin{equation}
    \label{eq:chung-lu}
    p_{ij} =
    \begin{cases}
        \frac{d_i d_j}{w} & i \ne j \\
        \frac{d_i^2}{2w}  & i = j
    \end{cases}
    \qquad
    w = \vb{1}^T \vb{d}
\end{equation}
where we allow self-loops (which contribute 2 to the degree).

These models nicely allow us to generate many other graphs by correctly specifying the degree distribution:
\begin{itemize}
    \item The power law graphs, where the coefficient is typically fit to a training set of data
    \item Random $d$-regular graphs, which is aas connected for $d \ge 3$, aas disconnected for $d < 3$
\end{itemize}
and also serve nicely as a \emph{null model} to normalize several measures discussed later (Sections \ref{sec:modularity, sec:benchmarks}).

\subsection{Quick checks}

\paragraph{Checks}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item For what $p$ would $\ER(n, p)$ be the uniform distribution over all graphs on $V = \arange{n}$?
    \item Let $X$ be the number of occurrences of a subgraph $H$ in $\ER(n, p)$, easy to calculate using linearity of expectation.
          If $\Ev(X) \to \infty$, does this imply $H$ is a motif aas?
    \item Approximate the Zipf distribution over $\R^{\ge 1}$ by $f(d) \propto d^{- \gamma}$.
          Verify the approximate moments in Equation \ref{eq:zipf}.
    \item Verify the expected degree in the Chung-Lu model (Equation \ref{eq:chung-lu}).
    \item How might one generate a graph according to the configuration model?
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Solutions}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item $p = 1/2$, where indeed each graph has probability $2^{-n}$ of being generated
    \item No. Even if the probability tends to $0$, the number of occurrences conditioned on existence may tend to infinity.
          \begin{minipage}{0.7\textwidth}
              Consider $H$ to the right, on $\ER(n, p = n^{-9/11})$, and $X$ number of occurrences in $\ER(n, p)$.
              The maximum subgraph density is $5/4$, and $p = n^{-9/11}$ is below threshold $n^{-4/5}$, so $\Pr{X = 0} \toP 1$.
              However, we may find $\Ev(X)$ explicitly:
              $$
                  \Ev(X) = \frac{1}{\mathbf{aut}(H)} \sum_{v_1,\ldots,v_5 \in V} 1_{H \subset G[v_1, \ldots, v_5]} = \binom{n}{5} \frac{5!}{2} p^6 = \Theta(n^{1/11}) \to \infty
              $$
          \end{minipage}
          \begin{minipage}{0.25\textwidth}
              \centering
              \begin{tikzpicture}[
                      every node/.style={circle, fill=black, inner sep=0pt, minimum size=5pt}
                  ]
                  \node (v1) at (0,1) {};
                  \node (v2) at (1,0) {};
                  \node (v3) at (0,-1) {};
                  \node (v4) at (-1,0) {};
                  \node (v5) at (2,0.5) {};
                  \draw (v1) -- (v2);
                  \draw (v2) -- (v3);
                  \draw (v3) -- (v4);
                  \draw (v4) -- (v1);
                  \draw (v2) -- (v4);
                  \draw (v2) -- (v5);
              \end{tikzpicture}
          \end{minipage}
    \item First, we find the normalizing factor, $f(d) = cd^{-\gamma}$, with $\gamma > 1$, and moments $\Ev(D^k)$ for $\gamma > k + 1$,
          $$
              \int_{1}^\infty cy^{- \gamma} \odif{y} = \frac{c}{\gamma - 1} = 1 \implies c = \gamma - 1
              \qquad
              \Ev(D^k) = (\gamma - 1) \int_1^\infty y^k y^{- \gamma} \odif{y} = (\gamma - 1) \frac{1}{\gamma - k - 1}
          $$
    \item Apply linearity of expectation:
          $$
              \Ev(\deg(v_i)) = 2 p_{ii} + \sum_{v_i \ne v_j \in V} p_{ij} = d_i \ab( 2 \frac{d_i}{2 w} + \sum_{v_i \ne v_j} \frac{d_j}{w} ) = d_i \frac{\sum_j d_j}{w} = d_i
          $$
    \item A simple algorithm is to create \emph{stubs} for each edge.
          Each vertex gets $d_i$ source stubs, and $d_i$ target stubs, and then a simple permutation (with no fixed points) suffices to match them together.
          It is well-known that $1/e$ proportion of such permutations are valid de-rangements, so rejection-sampling is efficient.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Centrality Measures}

This section addresses the question of detecting influential \emph{nodes} in a network.
We assign an influence score to each node, and then a typical pipeline proceeds by ranking them.
Indeed, as several methods are expensive on very large graphs, filtering by only collecting nodes in the $k$-core (i.e. maximal subgraph with min-degree at least $k$) is often performed ($k = 2$ usually).
It is also useful to describe the distribution of centrality.
A histogram or a survival curve is good, and the centralization $\max c(v) - \Ev(c(v))$ is also used.

For simplicity, the measures presented here are not normalized (cf. exercises).
We note that it is desirable for measures to have unit L1-norm, as well as between $[0, 1]$ to be interpretable across networks.

Our first set of measures are based on the adjacency matrix $A$, or potential normalized $\hat{A}$ with (column) sum $1$, where $A_{ij} = 1 \set{i \to j \in E}$ and are enumerated in Table \ref{tab:central-adj}.
These measure influence primarily via their ego-net.

\begin{table}[ht]
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tabular}{ccc}
            Measure               & Formula                                  & Notes                             \\
            \hline
            \hline
            Degree $\dagger$      & $A \vb{1}_n$                             & BA is based on degree centrality. \\
            Eigenvector $\dagger$ & $(I - A)^{-1} \vb{0}_n$                  & Perron eigenvector is unique.     \\
            Authority             & $(I - \alpha \beta A A^T)^{-1} \vb{0}_n$ & Center of incoming influence.     \\
            Hub                   & $(I - \alpha \beta A^T A)^{-1} \vb{0}_n$ & Point to authorities.             \\
            Katz                  & $(I - \alpha A^T)^{-1} \vb{1}_n$         & Based on damped random walk.      \\
            PageRank              & $(I - \alpha \hat{A}^T)^{-1} \vb{1}_n$   & Damped walk in stochastic matrix. \\
            \hline
        \end{tabular}
    \end{center}
    \caption{ \textbf{Adjacency matrix based centrality measures}. See text for additional details. $\dagger$ indicates undirected graphs. }
    \label{tab:central-adj}
\end{table}

Of course, it is straightforward to generalize degree and eigenvector centrality, although their interpretation may be less clear.
Authority and hub centrality are solutions to the following mutual recurrence $ \vb{x} = \alpha A^T \vb{y} $, and $ \vb{y} = \beta A \vb{x}$, and are not necessarily unique, but must correspond to the (same) principal eigenvalue.
PageRank and Katz centrality measure the occupancy of a node according to a random walk, e.g. $\vb{1}_n^T \sum_{k=1}^\infty (\alpha A)^k = (I - \alpha A^T)^{-1} \vb{1}$.
Iterative numerical methods (related to power iteration) are useful here, especially for sparse matrices (e.g. Lanczos).

Our next set of centrality measures are based instead on paths and distances (Table \ref{tab:central-dist}).
Let $\Pi(i, j, k)$ be the set of shortest paths between $v_i$ and $v_j$ containing $v_k$, $\Pi(i, j) = \bigcup_k \ell(i, j, k)$, and $\ell(\cdot) = \abs{\Pi(\cdot)}$.
\begin{table}[ht]
    \begin{center}
        \begin{tabular}{ccc}
            Measure      & Formula                                              & Notes                                 \\
            \hline
            \hline
            Closeness    & $\frac{1}{\sum_v d(u, v)}$                           & $d(u, u) = 0$ and $n$ if unreachable  \\
            Harmonic     & $\sum_{v \ne u} \frac{1}{d(u, v)}$                   & More stable than closeness, typically \\
            Eccentricity & $\frac{1}{\max_v d(u, v)}$                           & Related to diameter and radius        \\
            Betweenness  & $\sum_{i, j \ne u} \frac{\ell(i, j, u)}{\ell(i, j)}$ & Influential nodes are congested.      \\
            Efficiency   & $- \sum_{i, j \ne u} \frac{1}{d_{G - u}(i, j)}$      & Delta influence in the book.          \\
            \hline
        \end{tabular}
    \end{center}
    \caption{ \textbf{Path based centrality measures}. See text for additional details.}
    \label{tab:central-dist}
\end{table}

Each of the measures considered here straightforward to extend to groups of nodes, e.g. \emph{communities}.
They can help evaluate the overall organization of the network, as well as rank relative importance of various subsets of nodes.

\subsection{Quick checks}

\paragraph{Checks}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Normalize each of the centrality measures between $[0, 1]$.
    \item How might one describe the correlation between centrality measures?
          What pairs have high or low correlations?
    \item What is the computational cost for each of the centrality measures?
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Solutions}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item As eigenvector based measures are only defined up to scale, normalizing just requires picking a unit norm eigenvector.
          Katz is already normalized and pagerank requires a $(1 - \alpha) / n$ factor.
          Table \ref{tab:central-normalized} enumerates the normalization for the path based measures.
          \begin{table}[ht]
              \centering
              \begin{tabular}{ccccc}
                  Closeness                    & Harmonic                                & Eccentricity               & Betweenness                                                     & Efficiency                                                                         \\
                  \hline
                  \hline
                  $\frac{n-1}{\sum_v d(u, v)}$ & $\sum_{v \ne u} \frac{1}{(n-1)d(u, v)}$ & $\frac{1}{\max_v d(u, v)}$ & $\sum_{i, j \ne u} \frac{(n-1)(n-2) \ell(i, j, u)}{\ell(i, j)}$ & $1 - \frac{\sum_{i, j \ne u} d_{G - u}(i, j)^{-1}}{\sum_{i, j} d_{G}(i, j)^{-1}} $ \\
                  \hline
              \end{tabular}
              \caption{ \textbf{Normalized path based centrality measures}. }
              \label{tab:central-normalized}
          \end{table}
    \item We plot the pairwise Kendall $\tau$ correlation between centrality measures on the restricted Airport dataset\footnotemark
          \footnotetext{\url{https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/flashgordon/usa-airport-dataset}}.
          This correlation measures the number of concordant pairs minus discordant pairs in the ranking, normalized between $0$ and $1$ by $\binom{n}{2}$.

          The graph is disconnected, leading to $0$ variance of the eccentricity scoring and an undefined correlation between eccentricity and other measures.
          Overall, we see each of the measures are correlated, with the strongest correlation being between Katz and degree, as well as harmonic and closeness centralities.
          Moreover, the eigenvector centrality is similar to hub and authority.

          \begin{figure}[ht]
              \centering
              \includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figs/centrality_mat.pdf}
              \includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figs/centrality_dist.pdf}
              \includegraphics[width=0.32\textwidth]{figs/centrality_correlation.pdf}
              \caption{
                  \textbf{Centrality on the California Airports dataset}.
                  We show the distance and adjacency based centrality on a subset of the Airports dataset, restricted to within California flights.
                  Adjacency based measures are on the weighted (directed) graph by passengers, with degree and eigvec on $A + A^T$ symmetric graph.
                  Path based are on the unweighted undirected graph.
                  Figures (a) and (b) have nodes ordered by degree centrality, and are normalized to unit L1-norm.
                  Finally, we show the pairwise Kendall $\tau$ correlation in (c).
              }
          \end{figure}
    \item The matrix based are cheap (often Lanczos iteration converges in constant number of steps), taking time proportional to $O(m)$.
          The distance based ones are more expensive, with APSP taking $O(n^2 \log n + nm)$ time with Johnson's algorithm.
          $k$-core pruning is useful, as well as probabilistic estimation (Monte Carlo) is good.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Community Detection}

Community detection, as an unsupervised task, has many formulations.
Finding a partition of our vertex set, with certain requirements, we can discuss a node's role, e.g. if we consider degree, then
\begin{enumerate}
    \item A node's participation is given by $p(v) = 1 - \sum_i \ab( \frac{\abs{N(v)} \cap C_i}{\abs{N(v)}} )^2$
    \item A node's within-module $z$-score is given by $z(v) = \ab( \dint(v) - \mu(v) ) \sigma(v)^{-1}$.
    \item The anomaly score is $\text{cd}(v) = \deg(v) / \dint(v)$.
    \item The community association strength $\dint(v) / \deg(v) - \frac{\vol(C_i) - \deg(v)}{\vol(V)}$, normalized by Chung-Lu model.
\end{enumerate}

Community detection formulations argue about desirable cluster qualities.
Section \ref{sec:cluster-axioms} has a modern characterization, but for now, traditionally, for a cluster $C$, we may consider the following three characterizations:
\begin{itemize}
    \item Weak community, where $\sum_{v \in C} \dint(v) \ge \sum_{v \in C} \dext(v)$
    \item Strong community, where $\dint(v) \ge \dext(v) \forall v \in C$
    \item Community, where $p^{\text{int}}(v) = \frac{\dint(v)}{\abs{C}} > \frac{\dext(v)}{\abs{V \setminus C}} = p^{\text{ext}}(v)$
\end{itemize}

As an unsupervised approach, there are several useful guiding questions to tailor your method of choice.
How many clusters do we want, and what resolution are we studying?
What are the desirable qualities in a clustering?
Should clusters be overlapping?

\subsection{Linkage}

First, we sidestep the question of ``how many clusters'' by providing a view of many clusterings, for different scales.
\begin{minipage}{0.55\textwidth}
    In agglomerative clustering, we start with a singleton partition and merge pairs of clusters.
    In divisive clustering, we start with a giant partition and split apart clusters.
    Both are nicely visualized in a dendrogram, see for example the one on the right.
\end{minipage}
\begin{minipage}{0.4\textwidth}
    \centering
    \begin{tikzpicture}[
            scale=0.6,
            thick,
            line width=1.4pt,
            level distance=1.2cm,
            sibling distance=2.4cm
        ]

        % --- dendrogram ---
        \draw
        (0,0) -- (0,1)
        (0,1) -- (-2,1)
        (0,1) -- (2,1)

        (-2,1) -- (-2,2)
        (-2,2) -- (-3,2)
        (-2,2) -- (-1,2)

        (2,1) -- (2,2)
        (2,2) -- (1,2)
        (2,2) -- (3,2);

        % --- leaves ---
        \node[below] at (-3,2) {$A$};
        \node[below] at (-1,2) {$B$};
        \node[below] at (1,2) {$C$};
        \node[below] at (3,2) {$D$};

        % --- cluster count cut lines ---
        \draw[dotted, blue, very thick] (-4,0.5) -- (4,0.5);
        \node[blue, right] at (4,0.5) {\small 1 clusters};

        \draw[dotted, blue, very thick] (-4,1.5) -- (4,1.5);
        \node[blue, right] at (4,1.5) {\small 2 clusters};

        \draw[dotted, blue, very thick] (-4,2.5) -- (4,2.5);
        \node[blue, right] at (4,2.5) {\small 4 clusters};
    \end{tikzpicture}
\end{minipage}

The three typical strategies for agglomerative clustering, given a metric on our vertices, are:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Single-linkage, where cluster distance is the minimum distance between points
    \item Complete-linkage, where cluster distance is the maximum distance between points
    \item Average-linkage, where cluster distance is the mean distance between points
\end{enumerate}
These tend to produce ``stringy'' and ``round'' clusters respectively, with average-linkage also usually round (in Euclidean space). % TODO: a figure might be nice
For example, Rasvasz algorithm uses the following similarity function with average linkage:
$$
    s(v_i, v_j) = \frac{ \abs{N(v_i) \cap N(v_j)} + 1 \set{v_i v_j \in E} }{ \min( \deg(v_i), \deg(v_j) ) + 1 \set{v_i v_j \not \in E} }
$$
and Girvan-Newman is a divisive clustering algorithm, removing edges by an extension of betweenness for edges.

\subsection{Modularity}
\label{sec:modularity}

Specializing our discussion of clustering to graphs, modularity is perhaps one of the most commonly used (despite its many flaws).
It evaluates the quality of a clustering $\mathcal{C}$ by its improvement against the Chung-Lu null model,
$$
    q_G(\mathcal{C}) = \frac{1}{\abs{E}} \sum_{C_i \in \mathcal{C}} \Big[ \underbrace{\abs{E_G(C_i, C_i)}}_{\text{observed edges}} - \underbrace{\Ev_{G' \sim \mathcal{G}(\vb{d})} \abs{E_{G'}(C_i, C_i)}}_{\text{expected edges}} \Big] = \sum_{C_i \in \mathcal{C}} \Big[ \underbrace{\frac{\abs{E_G(C_i)}}{\abs{E}}}_{\text{edge contribution}} - \underbrace{\ab( \frac{\vol(C_i)}{\vol(V)} )^2}_{\text{degree tax}} \Big]
$$
Indeed, $q_G(C) \in [-0.5, 1]$, with $0$ being a singleton partition.
It is NP-Hard to optimize, but there are many good heuristics.
Namely, the Louvain algorithm iterates the following two stages:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Stage 1: local node movement; in order of a random permutation, move $v$ to community maximizes $q_G(\mathcal{C}')$.
    \item Stage 2: contract all communities into weighted (non-simple) graph, preserving degrees across components.
\end{enumerate}
As it is an unstable algorithm (meaning its performance varies widely with the permutation), it is an ideal candidate as a weak-learner.
ECG \parencite{Poulin2019-ip} runs stage $1$ of Louvain $\ell$ times to find $\mathcal{C}_\ell$, forming weights
$$
    w(u, v) = \lambda + (1 - \lambda) 1 \set{uv \in 2-\text{core}} \Ev_{\mathcal{C}_{\ell}} (uv \in \mathcal{C}_\ell)
$$
with default values $\ell = 16$ and $\lambda = 0.05$.
Finally, they run Louvain (repeating both stages) on the weighted graph to obtain their output clustering.
Leiden is an improvement over Louvain, with a similar heuristic but enforcing well-connectedness of communities (Louvain may output disconnected communities).

The biggest issue against modularity is its inductive bias against small clusters.
Namely, the Chung-Lu model is non-local, so that for two communities $C_i$ and $C_j$, we expect $\vol(C_i) \vol(C_j) / \vol(G)$ edges.
If both communities are smaller than $\sqrt{2 \abs{E}}$, then with even one edge between them, it is beneficial to merge\footnotemark.
\footnotetext{The ring of cliques is a canonical example, where small cliques with just one edge between them get merged.}
A simple patch is to add a resolution parameter $\gamma$, with the updated modularity function
$$
    q_G(\mathcal{C}, \gamma) = \sum_{C_i \in \mathcal{C}} \Big[ \frac{\abs{E_G(C_i)}}{\abs{E}} - \gamma \ab( \frac{\vol(C_i)}{\vol(V)} )^2 \Big]
$$
where communities maintain separated as long as the null proportion of edges $\le \gamma$ the empirical.
Of course, there is now the issue of picking a $\gamma$, difficult to know \emph{a priori}.
This is equivalent to adding a resistance to every node.

\subsection{Other Methods}

Now, we briefly examine a few other clustering algorithms.
The most scalable approach, label propagation, repeatedly moves a node to the partition matching the most of its neighbors.
Repeating for randomly selected nodes, it may not necessarily converge.

Spectral clustering is $k$-means clustering via the RBF kernel.
We seek $k$ components minimizing the RatioCut:
$$
    \mathcal{L}(S_1, \ldots, S_k) = \sum_{k=1}^K \frac{1}{\abs{S_k}} A(S_k, \bar{S}_k) = \sum_{k=1}^K \frac{1}{\abs{S_k}} \sum_{x \in S_k, y \not \in S_k} A_{xy}
$$
We can formulate an approximation to the NP-Hard optimization via the graph Laplacian $L = KK^T$, for $K \in \R^{n \times m}$ the (weighted) incidence matrix.
Let $H \in \R^{n \times k}$, $H_{ij} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\abs{S_j}}} 1\set{i \in S_j}$ be a (weighted) assignment, so $ \mathcal{L}(S_1, \ldots, S_k) = \Tr(H^TLH) $.
Indeed, $H$ is orthogonal (normalized by construction).
For any $f \in \R^n$,
$$
    \norm{K^T f}_2^2 = \sum_e (\sum_v k_{v, e} f_v)^2 = \sum_{uv \in E} \ab( \sqrt{A_{uv}} (f_u - f_v) )^2 = \frac{1}{2} \sum_{u, v \in V} A_{uv} (f_u - f_v)^2
$$
With $\abs{h_{ix} - h_{iy}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\abs{S_i}}} \abs{1\set{x \in S_i} - 1\set{y \in S_i}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\abs{S_i}}}1\set{\text{exactly one in } S_i}$, then letting $f = h$:
$$
    \Tr(H^T L H) = \norm{K^T H}_F^2 = \sum_{i=1}^k \norm{K^T \vb{h}_i}_2^2 = \sum_{i=1}^k \frac{1}{\abs{S_i}} \sum_{(x, y) \in (S_i, \bar{S}_i)} A_{xy} = \mathcal{L}(S_1, \ldots, S_k)
$$
Our (exact) problem seeks an orthonormal $H$ with discrete entries minimizing this trace.
Relaxing $H$ with entries in $\R$, our problem is now $\min_{H^T H = I_k} \Tr(H^T L H)$, which by Courant-Fisher are the $k$ smallest eigenvectors of $L$

