\subsection{Benchmarks}
\label{sec:benchmarks}

Evaluating a clustering algorithm for \emph{accuracy} requires a set of benchmarks with a ground-truth clustering.
Hence, there is a need to generate synthetic networks with a ground truth clustering\footnotemark.
\footnotetext{Ground-truth on empirical networks are sketchy. See, e.g. \textcite{Peel2017-gg}.}
Similarity functions on the contingency tables are useful, e.g. normalized/adjusted mutual information or adjusted rand index (concordant pairs).

The Stochastic Block Model extends ER with communities.
With communities $C_i$ of size $n_i$, we specify intra/inter-community edge probabilities $p_{ii}$ and $p_{ij}$.
In the planted partition model, $p_{ij} = p \delta_{ij} + q (1 - \delta_{ij})$.

The LFR model focuses specifically on recreating power-law graphs, with $\gamma$ and $\tau$ the community and degree Zipf parameters, as well as $\mu$ the fraction of inter-community \emph{neighbors}.
The original proposed model is clunky to specify exactly, and not-scalable.
Thus, the ABCD model improves on it, with $\gamma, \tau, \xi$ parameters, with $\xi$ the fraction of inter-community \text{edges}.
It is a union of $\ell$ communities (of sizes according to $\text{Zipf}(\gamma)$), with degrees by $(1 - \xi) \text{Zipf}(\tau)$, and a background graph with the inter-community edges.
ABCD+o extension allows for non-clustered outliers.

\subsection{Quick Checks}

\paragraph{Checks}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Are all weak communities strong communities, or vice versa?
          What about the third characterization?
    \item How long would an algorithm that checks every partition take?
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Solutions}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Strong communities are also weak.
          Weak communities are not necessarily strong.
          There are communities (defined by the proportion of edges) that are weak communities, as well as ones that aren't.
    \item The number of partitions of $\arange{n}$ is known as the Bell number, with
          $$
              B_{n} = \sum_{k=0}^n \binom{n-1}{k} B_k = \ab( \frac{n}{(e + o(1)) \ln n} )^n
          $$
          and grows super-exponentially. Indeed, $B_{15} \approx 1.4 \times 10^9$ (OEIS sequence \#\href{https://oeis.org/A000110}{A000110}).
\end{enumerate}

\section{Node Embeddings}

Another way of trying to obtain useful structural information is by embedding it into Euclidean space, either for reconstruction purposes, visualization, or to apply Machine learning algorithms (e.g. $k$-means, or deep learning).
For example, if our embedding puts two nodes close together, we may expect a missing link to be a false negative.
Formally, we seek $\mathcal{E}: V \to \R^k$, preserving some measure of proximity, e.g.
\begin{itemize}
    \item Adjacency (1st order proximity), or $k$-th order proximity the cosine distance of $k$-neighbors
    \item Katz index $\sum_{i=1}^\infty (\alpha A)^i = (I / \alpha - A)^{-1} A$, and personalized PageRank $(1 - \alpha) (I - \alpha \hat{A}^T)^{-1}$
    \item Adamic-Adar, a measure of volume of common neighbors $s(u, v) = \sum_{w \in N(u) \cap N(v)} \ab( \ln \deg(w) )^{-1}$
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Linear Embeddings}

Let $E \in \R^{k \times n}$ be an embedding, mapping each node to a (column) vector of dimension $k \ll n$.
We constrain $E$ to be zero-mean and orthogonal.
Local linear embedding argues $E$ should be similar for neighbors, thus optimizes
$$
    \Phi_{\text{LLE}}(E) = \norm{ (I - \hat{A})E^T }_F = \Tr( E (I - \hat{A})^T (I - \hat{A}) E^T )
$$
Here, $E^*$ are the $2$nd to $(k+1)$-th minimal eigenvectors (ignoring $\vb{1}_n$ of eigenvalue 0) of $(I - \hat{A})^T (I - \hat{A})$.
Note that isometries preserve $\Phi$.
Very related is $\Phi_{\text{LEM}} = \Tr( ELE^T )$, for $L$ Laplacian, or $\Phi(E)_{\text{HOPE}} = \norm{ S - E_s^T E_t }_F$, for source and target embeddings respectively, and $S$ similarity.

\subsection{Nonlinear Embeddings}

Decoder-encoder networks $D, E$ increase the expressivity of linear embeddings, e.g. optimizing
$$
    \Phi_{\text{SDNE}}(E) = \sum_i \norm{ (a_i - D(E(a_i))B_i }^2 + \alpha \Tr(E L E^T) + L_{\text{reg}}
$$
for $B_i$ (diagonal) vertex weights.
Another set of embeddings are based on the \emph{distribution hypothesis}.
Recall that Word2Vec finds an embedding by treating each row as logits for appearing as a neighbor and optimizing MLE.
Node2Vec creates ``sentences'' by running a random walk (DFS or BFS) and applying the Word2Vec procedure.

Finally, we mention an emerging field of structural embeddings, which encode data beyond adjacency.
Indeed, in the ReFeX procedure, given a set of initial structural features $\idx{\vb{f}_i}{0}$ for $v_i$,
$$
    \underbrace{\idx{\vb{h}_i}{k+1} \gets g( \set{ \idx{\vb{f}_j}{k} : v_j \in N(v_i) }}_{\text{Aggregate}},
    \qquad
    \underbrace{\idx{\vb{f}_i}{k+1} \gets \Pi_k \idx{\vb{h}_i}{k+1}}_{\text{Prune}}
$$
In particular, Graph Convolution Network, or the more scalable GraphSAGE (extension via sampling), runs
$$
    \idx{e}{s+1} = \sigma( \tilde{D}^{-1/2} \tilde{A} \tilde{D}^{-1/2} \idx{e}{s} \idx{W}{s} )
$$
where $\sigma$ activation and $\idx{W}{s}$ (trained) set of weights.
This can be semi-supervised, classifying unlabeled nodes.

\subsection{Quick Checks}

\paragraph{Checks}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Typically, our formulation of embedding supervised or unsupervised?
          Compare to spectral $k$-means.
    \item What is the vocabulary space of Node2Vec?
          What is its size relative to English?
    \item How might one evaluate an embedding algorithm?
\end{enumerate}

\paragraph{Solutions}

\begin{enumerate}
    \item Our description of recovering a proximity score is unsupervised.
          Spectral $k$-means clusters on the node-embedding of LEM (when normalized).
    \item The vocabulary space is each node, which can be millions or billions.
          Compare to English with thousands of words.
          DeepWalk addresses scalability with hierarchical softmax and Node2Vec implements negative sampling.
    \item \textcite{Kaminski2019-aj} propose using the Geometric Chung-Lu model, parameterized by degree distribution and node embeddings.
          Good embeddings reconstruct edges of $G$, (compare Hosmer-Lemeshow).
\end{enumerate}

\part{Appendix}

This part has content and derivations that are supplementary or illustrative to the content from book.
Much of it is from external readings, but many take inspiration from the material.

\section{Techniques for Random Graphs}

\subsection{ER-Graphs: connectivity and motifs}
\label{sec:er}

We consider the ER process $\ER_t$, seeking to understanding the behavior of the components as $t \to \infty$.
The main tool here will be Doob's Optional Stopping Theorem.
Fix $t$, and $v \in \ER_t$, and consider running BFS starting from $v$, letting $A_k$ be the size of our queue, i.e. $A_0 = 1$.
Then, the size of the components is $\tau_A \coloneq \min_{k} (A_k = 0) $.
We shall show\footnotemark that 1. $\Ev(\tau_A) \le \frac{1}{1 - c}$ when $c < 1$, and 2. $\Pr{\tau_A \ge \epsilon n} > \delta$ for $\epsilon$ satisfying $1 - \epsilon > e^{-c\epsilon}$, $\delta > 0$.
\footnotetext{In fact, both of these hold asymptotically almost-surely.}

Suppose $\mean{k} = c < 1$, i.e. $p = \frac{c}{n-1}$.
The number of adjacent neighbors is binomial distributed, in particular,
$$
    A_{k+1} = A_k + \BinomialD(n - k - A_k, p) - 1
$$
As we shall see, $t$ and $A_t$ are both small, so it suffices to bound it by $ B_{k+1} = A_{k+1} + \sum_{j=0}^k Y_k $ where $Y_k \sim \BinomialD(k + A_k - 1, p) $.
That is, we have the recurrence $B_{k+1} = B_k + \BinomialD(n - 1, p) - 1$.
As $B_k \ge A_k$, then we bound $\tau_A \le \tau_B \coloneq \min_{k} (B_k = 0) $.
Since $\Ev( \BinomialD(n - 1, p) ) = (n-1)p = c$, then by optionally stopping,
$$
    1 = \Ev( B_0 ) = \Ev( B_{\tau_B} + \tau_B(1 - c) ) = 0 + (1 - c) \Ev(\tau_B) \implies \Ev(\tau_B) = \frac{1}{1 - c}
$$
Thus, for $\mean{k} < 1$, then each component is of constant size in expectation.
Otherwise, supposing $\mean{k} > 1$, then we can apply similar argument with $Z_k \sim \BinomialD((n \epsilon - A_k - k), p)$, consider $C_{k+1} = A_{k+1} - \sum_{j=0}^k Z_k$ satisfying $C_{k+1} = C_k + \BinomialD(n(1 - \epsilon), p)$.
By standard results in random walks, as long as $\Ev(Z_k) - 1 > 0$, then with positive probability $\tau_C \ge k$.
Indeed, this holds for $\epsilon < 1 - c^{-1}$.
Further, with complementary counting, $\BinomialD(n - k - A_k, p) \sim \BinomialD(n - k, (1-p)^k)$, so we can moreover bound $\epsilon$ satisfying $1 - \epsilon - e^{- c \epsilon} > 0$.

Next, we can also discuss the probability of containing a motif, in terms of the maximum subgraph density.
Indeed, recall the Second-Moment Method, where for $X \ge 0$, we can bound the probability of $X$ being zero as
$$
    \Pr{X = 0} \le \Pr{ \abs{X - \Ev(x)} \ge \Ev(X) } \le \frac{\Var(X)}{\Ev(X)^2}
$$
Let $X$ be the number occurrences of $H$, with $h_v$ and $h_e$ vertices and edges, appearing as a subgraph in $\ER(n, p)$:
$$
    \Ev(X) = \frac{1}{\mathbf{aut}(H)} \sum_{v_1,\ldots,v_h \in V} 1\set{H \subset \ER[v_1, \ldots, v_h]} \propto n^{h_v} p^{h_e}
$$
Indeed, if $np^{-1/m(H)} \to 0$, then so does $\Ev(X)$ and $\Pr{X > 0}$.
Conversely, if $np^{-1/m(H)} \to \infty$, then we can bound the variance by writing $X = \sum X_k$ where $X_k$ indicates that a permutation of $h_v$ vertices contains $H$:
$$
    \Var(X) = \sum_k \Var(X_k) + \sum_{i \not \sim j} \cancel{\Cov(X_i, X_j)} + \sum_{i \sim j, i \ne j} \Cov(X_i, X_j) = O(n^{2n - h_v} p^{2m - h_e})
$$
with $i \sim j \iff X_i \not \indep X_j$, i.e. they share $\ge 2$ vertices.
Thus, $\frac{\Var(X)}{\Ev(X)^2} \to 0$, $\Pr{X > 0} \ge 1 - \frac{\Var(X)}{\Ev(X)^2} \to 1$.

\subsection{BA-Graphs: power-law distribution}
\label{sec:ba}

We briefly mention a more precise derivation of the degree distribution of a BA graph.
This is based on the \emph{rate equation}, where if we consider $N(k, t)$ the number of nodes of degree $k$ at a time $t$, with $p_k(t) = \frac{N(k, t)}{t}$, then
$$
    \Ev( \text{edges added to } N(k, t) \text{ per additional vertex} ) = m \frac{k}{2mt} N(k, t) = \frac{k}{2} p_k(t)
$$
Thus, we get the following difference equation
$$
    N(k, t+1) = N(k, t) + \underbrace{\frac{k-1}{2} p_{k-1}(t)}_{\text{promoting from degree } k-1} - \underbrace{\frac{k}{2} p_k(t)}_{\text{promoting to degree } k + 1}
$$
with initial condition $p_k = 0$ for $k < m$.
For large $t$, then $p_k(t)$ is stationary, and so
$$
    N(k, t+1) - N(k, t) = p_k = \frac{-1}{2} \ab( k p_k - (k-1) p_{k-1} )
$$
Now, solving this recurrence with one's favorite method, we find that
$$
    p_k = \frac{2m(m+1)}{k(k+1)(k+2)}
$$
which is very similar to our continuum approximation.
Indeed, approximate $k p_k - (k-1) p_{k-1} = \odv{(kp_k)}{k}$, then we arrive back at the standard continuum equation (after product rule).

\subsection{Regular-Graphs: number of cycles}

For $R_n$ the uniform distribution of $2$-regular graphs on $n$ vertices, we show that the number of cycles $Y_n$ is concentrated near $\frac{\ln n}{2}$.
Consider the following procedure (resembling DFS) for generating a $d$-regular graph:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Start at a source stub, and pair it with a target.
    \item Repeat step 1 from a source stub from the chosen paired vertex, or a uniform one if there are no remaining sources.
\end{enumerate}
There are $2n$ steps and thus $n$ steps of the algorithm.
Let $p_k$ be the probability of step $k$ closing a loop, so that $\Ev(Y_n) = \sum_{k=1}^n p_k$.
Let $s_k$ be the source vertex of the (unique) path at the $k$-th step.
Finally,
$$
    p_k = \frac{\# \text{target stubs of } s_k}{\# \text{target stubs remaining} } = \frac{1}{2(n-(k-1)) - 1}
$$
Thus we find our desired results:
\begin{align*}
    \Ev(Y_n) & = \sum_{k=1}^n \frac{1}{2(n-k) + 1} = \sum_{j=1}^{2n} \frac{1}{j} - \sum_{j=1}^n \frac{1}{2j}                                            \\
             & = (\ln 2n + \gamma) - \frac{\ln n + \gamma}{2} + o(1) = \frac{\ln n}{2} + \ln 2 + \frac{\gamma}{2} + o(1) \approx \frac{\ln n}{2} + 1.27
\end{align*}
and with Chernoff bounds, for each $X_k \in \set{0, 1}$ independent, then for any $0 < \delta < 1$, then\footnotemark
$$
    \Pr{Y_n \ge (1 + \sqrt{3} \delta) \Ev(Y_n)  } \le \exp{- \delta^2 \Ev(Y_n) } \le n^{-\delta^2 / 2} \to 0
$$
\footnotetext{The specific form I used is given by Lemma 13.2.5 in \url{https://sarielhp.org/p/notes/16/chernoff/cheat_sheet.pdf}}
\vspace{-2\baselineskip}

\subsection{Clustering Unweighted Graphs}
\label{sec:cluster-axioms}

We paraphrase the axioms a clustering algorithm $\mathcal{A}$ should satisfy, based on \textcite{Willson2024-wv}:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Richness: $\forall \mathcal{C}$ clustering of $\arange{n}$, $\exists E$ s.t. $\mathcal{A}(V, E) = \mathcal{C}$
    \item Consistency\footnotemark: $E'$ removes inter-cluster/adds intra-cluster edges, $\mathcal{A}(V, E')$ refines $\mathcal{A}(V, E')$.
    \item Connectivity: $\exists f: \R^+ \to \R^+$ unbounded and non-decreasing s.t. min-cut of all $C \in \mathcal{C}$ exceeds $f(\abs{C})$.
    \item Fixed point: applying $\mathcal{A}$ to any induced subgraph by clusters would return same clusters.
    \item Pair-of-cliques: $\exists n_0$ such that two cliques $K_{n_0}$ connected by edge are distinct clusters.
\end{enumerate}
\footnotetext{Standard consistency refines for strict equality of clusterings, but is unintuitive, e.g. a ring lattice.}

